{{notability|date=July 2015}}

The '''four walls''' (also known as the '''four wall system''') is a film production system whereby a [[Filmmaking|film production]] company rents a [[sound stage]] and associated space but then separately contracts for additional facilities and hires freelance staff.  The four walls system became prominent in the 1960s,<ref>{{cite book |last=Bloom Walden |first=Kiri |title=British Film Studios |publisher=Shire Publications |year=2013 |pages=47–48}}</ref> following the demise of the Hollywood [[studio system]] from 1948.<ref>{{cite book |last=Konigsberg |first=Ira |title=The Complete Film Dictionary |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=1997 |pages=397–399}}</ref> 
Some big studios, like [[Pinewood Studios]] in England, became four walls facilities<ref>{{cite web |title=The British film and television industries—decline or opportunity? |work=Select Committee on Communications |publisher=[[House of Lords]] |date=24 January 2010 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200910/ldselect/ldcomuni/37/37i.pdf |accessdate=4 October 2018 }}</ref> for independent film producers and television companies. These facilities no longer engage in the development or distribution of films.

The four walls system of production should not be confused with [[Four wall distribution|"four wall" distribution]].

