{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}

'''Parsi theatre''' is a generic term for an influential theatre tradition, staged by [[Parsi]]s, and theatre companies largely-owned by the Parsi business community, which flourished between 1850 and 1930s.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195644463.001.0001/acref-9780195644463-e-0473|title=The Oxford companion to Indian theatre|last=K|first=A|date=|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=|year=2004|isbn=9780199861248|editor-last=Lal|editor-first=Ananda|location=New Delhi|pages=|oclc=607157336|via=Oxford Reference}}</ref> The plays were in Gujarati, Hindi and Urdu, and after its beginning in Bombay, soon it developed into various travelling theatre companies, which toured across India, especially [[North India|north]] and [[western India]] (now [[Gujarat]] and [[Maharashtra]]), popularizing [[proscenium]]-style theatre in regional languages.

Entertainment-driven and incorporating [[musical theatre]] and folk theatre, in early 1900s, some Parsi theatre producers switched to new media like bioscope and subsequently many became film producers. The theatre diminished in popularity, with arrival of talkies era in [[Hindi cinema]] in 1930s. Post-independence, it experienced a revival in the 1950s, much like theatre in the rest of the India.{{Sfn|Kasbekar|2006|p=50}}{{Sfn|Dalmia|2004|p=60}}

==History==
The British community in Bombay had been staging theatre in English language for sometime by the mid-19th century. Parsis were a prominent business community in the city. In early 1850s, the students of [[Elphinstone College]] in Mumbai had formed a dramatic society and started performing [[Shakespeare]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding 20th century Parsi theatre|date=18 December 2011|first=Rahul|last=Chandawarkar|publisher=Daily News & Analysis|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-understanding-20th-century-parsi-theatre-1627314|accessdate=2014-06-04 }}</ref> The first Parsi Theatre company called "Pārsī Nāṭak Maṇḍali" performed their first play ''Roostum Zabooli and Sohrab'' in 1853, followed by ''King Afrasiab and Rustom Pehlvan'' and ''Pādśāh Faredun''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nicholson 2015, p. 617.|publisher=|doi=10.1080/00856401.2015.1080211 | volume=38|journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies|pages=613–638}}</ref> By 1860 over 20 Parsi theatre groups were formed in Mumbai.{{Sfn|Palsetia|2001|p=184}}

The early plays in Parsi theatre presented Indianized versions of [[Shakespeare]]’s plays, by turning them into folk performances, with dozens of songs added in. Soon Indian legends, epic and mythological tales made an appearance as source material. As Parsi theatre companies started travelling across [[North India]], they employed native writers to churn out scripts in [[Hindustani language]], mix of Hindi and Urdu.<ref>[[#Han|Hansen, p. 75]]</ref>

Later Parsi plays "blended [[realism (arts)|realism]] and fantasy, music and dance, narrative and spectacle, earthy dialogue and ingenuity of stage presentation, integrating them into a dramatic discourse of [[melodrama]]". For mass appeal the plays incorporated humour, melodious songs and music, sensationalism and stagecraft.<ref name="Gokulsing-98">{{cite book| last = K. Moti Gokulsing| first = K. Gokulsing, Wimal Dissanayake| title = Indian Popular Cinema: A Narrative of Cultural Change| year = 2004| publisher = Trentham Books| page = 98 }}</ref> The success of Parsi theatre lead to the development of theatre in regional languages notably modern [[Gujarati theatre]], [[Marathi theatre]] and [[Hindi theatre]].{{Sfn|Hochman|1984|p=38}} Later it led  to the development of [[Hindi cinema]] (Bollywood), the effect of Parsi theatre is still evident in the [[Masala film]] genre of [[Indian cinema]], {{Sfn|Joughin|1997|p=129}}<ref name="Gokulsing-98"/> and especially in [[Music of Bollywood|Bollywood film songs]].<ref name="MehtaPandharipande2010">{{cite book|last1=Mehta|first1=Rini Bhattacharya|last2=Pandharipande|first2=Rajeshwari|title=Bollywood and Globalization: Indian Popular Cinema, Nation, and Diaspora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cgZTUn00crMC&pg=PA176|year=2010|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-1-84331-833-0|page=36}}</ref>

Parsi theatre was also popular in South-East Asia, where it was known as ''Wyang Parsi'' and often imitated.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=21gkDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA68&lpg=PA68&dq=Wayang+Parsi&source=bl&ots=ePdhi1Qpxd&sig=DCdXCSTptdFnmXWhLDxUZB4iu5w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc28H2_N_XAhXBDsAKHWHWDd8Q6AEISjAL#v=onepage&q=Wayang%20Parsi&f=false|title=Hindustani Traces in Malay Ghazal: 'A song, so old and yet still famous'|last=Meddegoda|first=Chinthaka Prageeth|last2=Jähnichen|first2=Gisa|date=2016-09-23|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=9781443899987|language=en}}</ref>

In 1981, Mumbai-based theatre director [[Nadira Babbar]], started her theatre group ''Ekjute'' (Together), with the production of ''[[Yahudi Ki Ladki]]'', which revived the Parsi theatre style, and is considered one of its finest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian theatre at the crossroads|work=The Tribune|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000625/spectrum/main9.htm|date=25 June 2000|accessdate=2014-08-27}}</ref>

